In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April as National Child Abuse Prevention Month. He emphasizes the importance of raising children and the responsibility of parents, communities, and the nation in ensuring their well-being. The president highlights the prevalence of child neglect and abuse in the United States, with over half a million children affected each year. He emphasizes that a strong and informed family unit, supported by relatives, friends, neighbors, and communities, is crucial in preventing child abuse. The article also mentions the administration's commitment to prioritizing children's health and well-being, including supporting services that protect children from abuse and neglect, investing in early learning programs, and providing tools for identifying and preventing abuse. President Obama encourages all Americans to participate in programs and activities that help prevent child abuse and meet the physical, emotional, and developmental needs of children.